+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Apple, Opera, and Mozilla Push For HTML5                           |
|   from the overdue-updates dept.                                   |
|   posted by kdawson on Thursday April 12, @12:30 (The Internet)    |
|   http://developers.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/12/152245    |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]foo fighter writes "The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) has been
slumbering the past several years: HTML was [1]last updated in 1999,
XHTML was [2]last updated in 2002, and no one is taking seriously their
largely incompatible work on [3]'next-generation' XHTML or
[4]'modularized' XHTML. Both HTML and XHTML are in sorry need of removing
deprecated items while being updated to reflect the current practices of
web and browser developers and remaining compatible with legacy
Recommendations. The much more open and transparent [5]WHATWG (Web
Hypertext Application Technology Working Group), formed in 2004 to
address this problem, and has been hard at work on developing a draft
spec for [6]HTML5 to update and replace legacy versions of both HTML and
XHTML. The quality of this work has reached the point that [7]Apple,
Opera, and Mozilla have requested the adoption of HTML5 as the new 'W3C
Recommendation' for Web development."

Discuss this story at:
    http://developers.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/12/152245

Links:
    0. mailto:foofighterbarlover@gmail.com
    1. http://www.w3.org/TR/html401/
    2. http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/
    3. http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml2/
    4. http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml11/
    5. http://blog.whatwg.org/faq/
    6. http://www.whatwg.org/specs/
    7. http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/public-html/2007Apr/0429.html


